new perspectives on the indigenous cultures of the americas lecture series mark watson events at stanford new perspectives on the indigenous cultures of the americas lecture series mark watson facebook twitter email print add to calendar alan michelson's third bank of the river diplomatic aesthetics and globalization what would it mean to decolonize north america today this pressing question is considered by mohawk artist alan michelson's third bank of the river installed in june 2009 in the passenger lobby of the american border station at massena new york here viewers encounter the work as they travel across the disputed border zone between the united states canada and the akwesasne mohawk nation by recovering histories and strategies of native cultural diplomacy third bank engages international viewers in an argument about justice challenging a largely non native audience to recognize the ethical legitimacy of native empowerment and the contemporary relevance of indigenous political and cultural models mark watson suggests this can be understood as a version of what hal foster calls the archival impulse in contemporary art adapted to the ends of native sovereignty in the context of a neoimperial globalization mark watson is a ph d candidate in the department of art history and archaeology at columbia university his research explores the relationship of contemporary native american art indigenous political philosophy and globalization when wednesday february 8 2012 5 30 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s where cummings art building ar2 map audience general public faculty staff students alumni friends tags arts lecture reading visual sponsor department of art & art history contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free an open to the public permalink http events stanford edu events 309 30919 more info last modified february 8 2012
